00:56:03.480 --> 00:56:05.130
I'm just wondering--
so would you

00:56:05.130 --> 00:56:12.030
consider your experiment as a
counterexample to free will?

00:56:12.030 --> 00:56:14.585
Do you have any response
from philosophers yet?

00:56:14.585 --> 00:56:15.210
MORAN CERF: OK.

00:56:15.210 --> 00:56:20.050
So I get asked a lot about free
will as a philosophical idea.

00:56:20.050 --> 00:56:23.890
And the reality is that we don't
have a good answer in the sense

00:56:23.890 --> 00:56:26.369
that-- so we get you
beyond the moment

00:56:26.369 --> 00:56:27.410
you experience free will.

00:56:27.410 --> 00:56:30.350
So if I ask you when you made
a choice to go left or right,

00:56:30.350 --> 00:56:31.144
you would say now.

00:56:31.144 --> 00:56:32.810
And we show you that
this was a mistake.

00:56:32.810 --> 00:56:35.180
Surely the moment you made a
choice is not the moment that

00:56:35.180 --> 00:56:36.055
really made a choice.

00:56:36.055 --> 00:56:38.470
We can go back
milliseconds, seconds,

00:56:38.470 --> 00:56:41.734
before the choice was made and
predict it with high accuracy.

00:56:41.734 --> 00:56:43.650
But it doesn't mean that
there's no free will.

00:56:43.650 --> 00:56:45.190
It just maybe happened before.

00:56:45.190 --> 00:56:47.400
Maybe free will
happened at time zero,

00:56:47.400 --> 00:56:50.284
and just you experienced
it as free will times four.

00:56:50.284 --> 00:56:51.700
So we don't have
the answer to it.

00:56:51.700 --> 00:56:52.949
It's like the Big Bang theory.

00:56:52.949 --> 00:56:54.880
We can go all the way
to the very beginning,

00:56:54.880 --> 00:56:56.980
but we couldn't go beyond.

00:56:56.980 --> 00:56:59.680
I can tell you that we ask
questions of our subjects

00:56:59.680 --> 00:57:01.010
in this experiment.

00:57:01.010 --> 00:57:02.787
And we can say that
there's psychology,

00:57:02.787 --> 00:57:04.370
like the patients
when they experience

00:57:04.370 --> 00:57:05.994
that their choices
are being predicted,

00:57:05.994 --> 00:57:09.000
they do have all kinds of
questioning about more life,

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:11.680
like they become a little bit
more protective of rights.

00:57:11.680 --> 00:57:13.630
They defend criminals
a little bit different.

00:57:13.630 --> 00:57:16.820
It kind of brings big
questions about life.

00:57:16.820 --> 00:57:22.780
The counter answer is an example
that I read a few weeks ago.

00:57:22.780 --> 00:57:27.290
There is a gene that if you
carry this gene, I think,

00:57:27.290 --> 00:57:30.640
you're nine times more likely
to be involved in a crime.

00:57:30.640 --> 00:57:33.850
Generally, I think nine
of the people in death row

00:57:33.850 --> 00:57:34.614
carry this gene.

00:57:34.614 --> 00:57:36.280
And there's other
statistics about this.

00:57:36.280 --> 00:57:38.070
And it's the Y chromosome.

00:57:38.070 --> 00:57:41.504
So most bad things
are caused by men.

00:57:41.504 --> 00:57:42.920
So we can predict
when you're born

00:57:42.920 --> 00:57:45.607
that you're going to be on
the side of potentially bad--

00:57:45.607 --> 00:57:47.440
it doesn't allow us to
do anything about it.

00:57:47.440 --> 00:57:49.231
We have to wait for
you to do those things.

00:57:49.231 --> 00:57:52.070
So when we came to judges with
our results and said, look,

00:57:52.070 --> 00:57:54.790
we can actually help you decode
the intentions of people.

00:57:54.790 --> 00:57:57.130
And they said, look, you
guys, scientists came to us

00:57:57.130 --> 00:58:00.200
in the 1920s with
phrenology, and you told us

00:58:00.200 --> 00:58:02.892
that you can touch the scalp
and figure out when someone

00:58:02.892 --> 00:58:04.100
is going to do something bad.

00:58:04.100 --> 00:58:06.460
And then you came to us 10 years
after and you said, no, no.

00:58:06.460 --> 00:58:07.251
This was a mistake.

00:58:07.251 --> 00:58:08.514
EEG's the right way to go.

00:58:08.514 --> 00:58:10.430
And then you came to us
in the '70s with FMRI.

00:58:10.430 --> 00:58:12.263
And now you're coming
to us with your tools.

00:58:12.263 --> 00:58:14.200
We're going to wait a
few decades before we're

00:58:14.200 --> 00:58:16.000
going to let you actually
predict behavior,

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:16.870
because you change your mind.

00:58:16.870 --> 00:58:17.953
And I think they're right.

00:58:17.953 --> 00:58:19.840
I think that we can
predict to some extent,

00:58:19.840 --> 00:58:21.173
but we're still making mistakes.

00:58:21.173 --> 00:58:23.830
And that's enough to not be
a useful tool to really drive

00:58:23.830 --> 00:58:25.904
a car with just your thoughts.

00:58:25.904 --> 00:58:27.070
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

00:58:27.070 --> 00:58:28.030
MORAN CERF: Sure.

