00:58:52.430 --> 00:58:56.140
at something like the
feed that you sent to us,

00:58:56.140 --> 00:58:58.359
we'd send to your cardio
muscles or whatever.

00:58:58.359 --> 00:59:00.150
Is that the two main
things that are there,

00:59:00.150 --> 00:59:04.900
or is there something much
more advanced than there, too?

00:59:04.900 --> 00:59:07.214
MORAN CERF: So the
neuroscience of our work

00:59:07.214 --> 00:59:09.130
has kind of two angles--
one very applicative,

00:59:09.130 --> 00:59:10.170
one very theoretical.

00:59:10.170 --> 00:59:13.120
So the application is we're
trying to be really, really

00:59:13.120 --> 00:59:15.190
good in decoding thoughts
so we can teach you

00:59:15.190 --> 00:59:17.580
how to control things
outside of general behavior.

00:59:17.580 --> 00:59:20.350
So we want to help people
that smoke to stop smoking.

00:59:20.350 --> 00:59:23.230
We want to help people who
cannot move their arms control

00:59:23.230 --> 00:59:25.290
a robotic arm or a
wheelchair and move around.

00:59:25.290 --> 00:59:26.290
This is the application.

00:59:26.290 --> 00:59:29.272
And then we just try to
improve the accuracy.

00:59:29.272 --> 00:59:31.730
If right now, we can predict
your choice 9 out of 10 times,

00:59:31.730 --> 00:59:33.340
I want to get to 10 out of 10.

00:59:33.340 --> 00:59:34.060
That's that.

00:59:34.060 --> 00:59:36.274
The other angle is neuroscience.

00:59:36.274 --> 00:59:38.190
The fact that we found
out how the brain coded

00:59:38.190 --> 00:59:43.932
a thought in those electrical
chemical spikes is still crude.

00:59:43.932 --> 00:59:45.890
Sometimes you heard that
it goes from [TAPPING]

00:59:45.890 --> 00:59:47.320
to [RAPIDLY TAPPING].

00:59:47.320 --> 00:59:49.750
But we don't know
exactly why is it

00:59:49.750 --> 00:59:51.460
that speed and not that speed.

00:59:51.460 --> 00:59:55.210
And presumably this carries
the most interesting part

00:59:55.210 --> 00:59:56.770
of our life.

00:59:56.770 --> 00:59:58.450
The brain doesn't
randomly spike.

00:59:58.450 --> 00:59:59.800
Every spike means something.

00:59:59.800 --> 01:00:02.342
So we now try to not
just be binary and say

01:00:02.342 --> 01:00:03.800
Marilyn Monroe,
not Marilyn Monroe,

01:00:03.800 --> 01:00:06.385
but actually why is it coding
Marilyn Monroe this way

01:00:06.385 --> 01:00:07.240
and not that way.

01:00:07.240 --> 01:00:08.530
What are the associations?

01:00:08.530 --> 01:00:11.940
If Marilyn Monroe
reminds you of JFK,

01:00:11.940 --> 01:00:13.950
will the cell that
coded Marilyn Monroe

01:00:13.950 --> 01:00:15.595
fire for Kennedy as well?

01:00:15.595 --> 01:00:16.970
If you fire for
Kennedy, will you

01:00:16.970 --> 01:00:18.720
fire for Bobby Kennedy
and other Kennedys?

01:00:18.720 --> 01:00:20.020
Or just for one?

01:00:20.020 --> 01:00:20.655
How far is it?

01:00:20.655 --> 01:00:22.780
So those are interesting
questions philosophically.

01:00:22.780 --> 01:00:24.940
When in your life
did you acquire this?

01:00:24.940 --> 01:00:26.870
Why did it pick this
cell and not that cell?

01:00:26.870 --> 01:00:30.340
So the neuroscience is really
both interesting and in need

01:00:30.340 --> 01:00:31.720
of people with technical skills.

01:00:31.720 --> 01:00:33.250
AUDIENCE: Sure.

01:00:33.250 --> 01:00:38.380
The second question was
how transferable is this

01:00:38.380 --> 01:00:39.910
from one person to the other?

01:00:39.910 --> 01:00:42.710
Because I'm assuming that the
way one person has an idea--

01:00:42.710 --> 01:00:44.434
their knowledge base
about Marilyn Monroe

01:00:44.434 --> 01:00:46.600
is entirely different from
how another person thinks

01:00:46.600 --> 01:00:48.700
about the idea of
Marilyn Monroe.

01:00:48.700 --> 01:00:51.519
So do you see this
being applied from--

01:00:51.519 --> 01:00:54.060
you know, like say something's
standing between us on a lane,

01:00:54.060 --> 01:00:57.760
or maybe 10 people--
maybe like 1,000 people

01:00:57.760 --> 01:01:00.340
see a billboard in Times
Square, and then somebody

01:01:00.340 --> 01:01:02.350
captures that data
to figure out just

01:01:02.350 --> 01:01:04.810
what phased from yesterday
in terms of thoughts?

01:01:04.810 --> 01:01:07.480
Or do you think this is not
transferable at all based

01:01:07.480 --> 01:01:09.070
on the data that you've seen?

01:01:09.070 --> 01:01:10.590
MORAN CERF: So high
level, it's very possible.

01:01:10.590 --> 01:01:11.320
Low level, it's not.

01:01:11.320 --> 01:01:13.090
So high but meaning
in all of our brains

01:01:13.090 --> 01:01:16.220
that part of our brain that
codes people is the same.

01:01:16.220 --> 01:01:18.502
So there's a part
that it comes to life

01:01:18.502 --> 01:01:20.960
when you think Marilyn Monroe,
when I think Marilyn Monroe.

01:01:20.960 --> 01:01:22.010
But within this
spot, there are many,

01:01:22.010 --> 01:01:24.300
many millions or billions
of neurons and there

01:01:24.300 --> 01:01:25.620
are organizationally chaotic.

01:01:25.620 --> 01:01:27.953
Like your Marilyn Monroe cell
is here and mine is there.

01:01:27.953 --> 01:01:29.834
They're all in the
same stadium, but you

01:01:29.834 --> 01:01:31.750
might sit in section
one, and I'm section two.

01:01:31.750 --> 01:01:35.500
And we didn't find any way
to kind of map one brain

01:01:35.500 --> 01:01:38.805
to another in that
high level notion.

01:01:38.805 --> 01:01:40.180
But there's a
Nobel Prize hanging

01:01:40.180 --> 01:01:44.170
on the understanding of how
the brain actually decides

01:01:44.170 --> 01:01:45.390
which cell to code this.

01:01:45.390 --> 01:01:46.931
There's all kinds
of questions, like,

01:01:46.931 --> 01:01:48.760
how do I structure
the fragment memories

01:01:48.760 --> 01:01:49.690
and moving them over night?

01:01:49.690 --> 01:01:50.890
And there's a lot of
theories why that is,

01:01:50.890 --> 01:01:53.530
but no one actually knows
when the brain chose to put it

01:01:53.530 --> 01:01:55.400
here and not there and why.

01:01:55.400 --> 01:01:58.030
Now, the reason it's
really, really interesting

01:01:58.030 --> 01:02:00.910
is I can map your brain and find
Marilyn Monroe, and the Eiffel

01:02:00.910 --> 01:02:03.080
Tower, and your mom and
dad cells in your brain.

01:02:03.080 --> 01:02:04.780
And I can find it in his brain.

01:02:04.780 --> 01:02:06.400
And once we do that,
we can actually

01:02:06.400 --> 01:02:07.610
override communication.

01:02:07.610 --> 01:02:11.410
So if think about historically,
we evolved in a lot of ways

01:02:11.410 --> 01:02:12.714
in the last decades.

01:02:12.714 --> 01:02:14.380
But communication is
still the same way.

01:02:14.380 --> 01:02:16.050
If you find a
Neanderthal right now,

01:02:16.050 --> 01:02:20.950
he and you would speak the
same way-- vocal cords, mouth.

01:02:20.950 --> 01:02:23.150
And we know it's a
pretty slow process.

01:02:23.150 --> 01:02:28.360
I can think thoughts in about
600 thoughts per second--

01:02:28.360 --> 01:02:29.110
per minute, sorry.

01:02:29.110 --> 01:02:32.140
I'm going to check my
brain, but I can talk then

01:02:32.140 --> 01:02:34.240
only at 150 words per minute.

01:02:34.240 --> 01:02:37.600
I can do 300, but
you can do 150.

01:02:37.600 --> 01:02:39.150
So we are very slow.

01:02:39.150 --> 01:02:41.085
We think a lot faster
than our bandwidth

01:02:41.085 --> 01:02:42.737
is to communicate them.

01:02:42.737 --> 01:02:44.320
And we also receive
them a bit faster.

01:02:44.320 --> 01:02:47.627
Clearly there is a barrier
here that if we overcome,

01:02:47.627 --> 01:02:49.960
if I can just find the Marilyn
Monroe cell in your brain

01:02:49.960 --> 01:02:51.450
and in my brain,
and when I think it,

01:02:51.450 --> 01:02:52.366
I just zap your brain.

01:02:52.366 --> 01:02:56.260
And you immediately see it, we
can start using high frequency

01:02:56.260 --> 01:02:57.100
communication.

01:02:57.100 --> 01:02:58.467
And that's pretty cool.

01:02:58.467 --> 01:02:59.300
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

